PreWhiten.arma<- function(x , ar = NULL, ma = 0){
        if(is.null(ar) && is.null(ma)) print("both ar and ma coefficients are empty!")
        pwData = numeric(0)
        m = as(modelCoef(new("ArmaModel", ar = ar, ma = ma)), "list")
        eps = numeric(length(x))
        pwData = xarmaFilter(m, x =x, eps = eps, whiten = TRUE) 
        pwData[!is.na(pwData)]
}
PreWhiten.ar<- function(x , ar = NULL){
        if(is.null(ar)) print(" autoregressive coefficients are empty!")
        pwData = numeric(0)
        pwData = filter(x, c(1, -ar),method=c("convo"),sides=1) 
        pwData[!is.na(pwData)]
}

LBTest<- function(res, nPQ = 0, m = 24, ifPlot = FALSE){
        stopifnot(nPQ >= 0, m >= 1, m > nPQ)
        n <- length(res)
        lags <- 1:m
        df <- (nPQ+1):m 
        ra <- (acf(res, lag.max = m, plot = FALSE)$acf)[-1]
        QQ <- n * (n + 2) * cumsum((ra^2)/(n - (1:m)))[df]
        
        pv <- 1 - pchisq(QQ, df)
        QQ <- round(QQ, 2)
        a <- matrix(c(df, QQ, pv), ncol = 3)
        dimnames(a) <- list(rep("", length(QQ)), c("m", "Qm", "pvalue"))
        if(ifPlot){
                plot(x = a[,1],y = a[,3],
                     ylim = c(0,1), pch = 15, col = "lightblue",
                     ylab = "p-value", xlab = "m",
                     main = "Ljung-Box portmanteau test")
                abline(h =0.05, col =2)
                abline(h =0.01, col =4)
                grid()
        }else {
                a
        }
}

ANS:
Firstly I used auto.arima() to fit the best ARMA model for changes of real GDP(X). An ARMA(2, 0) model is selected based on AIC and we called it mod.
By checking the ACF, PACF plots, all the values are inside the confidence interval, hence we can say that the model residuals are white noise. Furthermore, we used the provided LBTest function to check the model residuals. There are 2 parameters in the fitted model, so the Ljung-Box statistic is distributed as a \(X^2_{m-2}\), where m is a preselected lag for the test. Since most of the p-values of the test statistics are above the 5% significance level(the dashed red line), the fitted model mod is adequacy.
Then I prewhitened X and Y(delinquency rates) and plotted the cross-correlation plot. As indicated in the cross-correlation plot, we ignored the postive lags and observed that there are 5 spikes at lag 0 to lag -5. Therefore, \(RGDP_t, RGDP_{t-1}, RGDP_{t-2}, RGDP_{t-3}, RGDP_{t-4}, RGDP_{t-5}\) should include in the transfer function noise model.

4. Conduct the model adequacy tests (diagnostics) on the above models and conclude your inference.

  • Linear Regression Model adequacy tests

  • TFN Model adequacy tests

ANS:
The Ljung-Box portmanteau test checks whether the residuals of the model follow white noise, the cross-correlation test checks whether there is correlation between the residuals and the inputs(chaneg of real GDP, \(X_t\)). If all the p-values are above 5% significance level, the fitted model is adequate.
For the Linear Regression Model, the p-values of the cross-correlation test are all above 0.05, but the p-values of the Ljung-Box portmanteau test are not, therefore the residuals of this model is highly correlated. The Linear Regression Model is not adequate.
For the TFN Model, the p-values of the Ljung-Box portmanteau test are above 0.05. On the other hand, the p-values of the cross-correlation test are less than 0.05, but greater than 0.01, and it become more significant as m increases. Therefore, the TFN model is adequate.

    

Conduct the out of sample forecasts of the above fitted models using the remaining observations. Calculate the forecast performance using Mean squared error (MSE), Mean absolute error (MAE), and Mean absolute percentage error (MAPE):

\[MSE = \sqrt \frac{\sum_{i=1}^L (y_{t+i}-\hat y_t(i))^2}{L}\] \[MAE = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^L \left|y_{t+i}-\hat y_t(i)\right|}{L}\] \[MAPE = \frac{1}{L}\sum_{i=1}^L \left|1-\frac{\hat y_t(i)}{y_{t+i}}\right|,\]

where \(\hat y_t(i)\) denotes the forecast at origin \(t\) with lead time \(i\)

#' @forecast using linear regression
#'
test_data=window(data,start=c(2018,4))
test_data_lm = as.data.frame(test_data)
linear_pred = forecast(lm, newdata = test_data_lm[,-1])



#' @calculate MSE, MAE, MAPE 
#'
MSE_lm = mean((test_data_lm$CL-linear_pred$mean)^2)%>%sqrt()
MAE_lm = mean(abs(test_data_lm$CL-linear_pred$mean))
MAPE_lm = mean(abs(1-linear_pred$mean/test_data_lm$CL))*100
res1 = cbind (MSE_lm,MAE_lm,MAPE_lm)
colnames(res1) = c("MSE","MAE","MAPE")
kable(res1, digits = 2, caption = "Out-of-sample Forecasts Accuracy Using LM")
Out-of-sample Forecasts Accuracy Using LM
MSE MAE MAPE
1.6 1.15 53.18 
#' @forecast using tfn
#'

tfn_pred = forecast(mod.tfn,xreg = test_data[,-1])

#' @calculate MSE, MAE, MAPE 
#'
MSE_tfn = mean((test_data_lm$CL-tfn_pred$mean)^2)%>%sqrt()
MAE_tfn = mean(abs(test_data_lm$CL-tfn_pred$mean))
MAPE_tfn = mean(abs(1-tfn_pred$mean/test_data_lm$CL))*100
res = cbind (MSE_tfn,MAE_tfn,MAPE_tfn)
colnames(res) = c("MSE","MAE","MAPE")
kable(res, digits = 2, caption = "Out-of-sample Forecasts Accuracy Using TFN")
Out-of-sample Forecasts Accuracy Using TFN
MSE MAE MAPE
0.78 0.45 21.25

ANS:
RMSE is the standard deviation of the residuals, lower values of RMSE indicate better fit. The RMSE for the linear model and the TFN model are 1.6 and 0.78 respectively. Therefore TFN model has better fit. MAE measures the average of the errors in a set of forecasts regardless of the direction, the lower the values the smaller the error. The MAE for the two models are 1.15 and 0.45 respectively, therefore TFN model has less error. The smaller the MAPE the better the forecast, the MAPE for the two models are 53.18 and 21.25 respectively, therefore TFN model makes better forecasts. To sum up, the TFN model is better than the Linear model.

Conduct the same out of sample forecast analysis using forecast combination of the fitted TFN model and ARIMA model (equal weight and MSE weighting). Compare its forecast metrics with those in the previous two questions

  • Forecast combination:
    The combined forecaster \(\hat f_t(i)\) may be given by \[\hat f_t(i) = w_a ~ \hat y_t^{(a)}(i)+w_b~ \hat y_t^{(b)}(i),\] where the superscripts \((a)\) and \((b)\) stand for transfer function noise model and ARIMA model, respectively. For the equal weight scheme, \(w_a = w_b = 0.5\), and for the MSE weighting scheme, its weights is the solution of \[\min_{w_a} \sqrt {\sum_{t=1}^n \{y_t -w_a \hat y_t^{(a)}-(1-w_a)\hat y_t^{(b)}\}^2},\] where \(w_a, w_b \in[0,1]\), \(w_a+w_b=1\), and \(\hat y_t^{(a)}\) denote the fitted value at time \(t\) in the training sample and \(n\) is the series length.
#' @calculate MSE, MAE, MAPE for the equal weight forecast
#'
equ_weight_pred= 0.5*tfn_pred$mean + 0.5*arima_pred$mean

MSE_equ_weight = mean((test_data_lm$CL-equ_weight_pred)^2)%>%sqrt()
MAE_equ_weight = mean(abs(test_data_lm$CL-equ_weight_pred))
MAPE_equ_weight = mean(abs(1-equ_weight_pred/test_data_lm$CL))*100
res3 = cbind (MSE_equ_weight,MAE_equ_weight,MAPE_equ_weight)
res33 = rbind(res3,res22,res1)
colnames(res33) = c("MSE","MAE","MAPE")
rownames(res33) = c("Combined_equalWeight","ARIMA Model","TFN Model","LM")
kable(res33, digits = 2, caption = "Out-of-sample Forecasts Accuracy")

#' @calculate MSE scheme weight
#'

f = function(w){sqrt(sum((sub_data[,1]-w*mod.tfn$fitted - (1-w)*arima$fitted)^2))}
w = optimize(f,c(0,1))$minimum
weighted_pred= w*tfn_pred$mean + (1-w)*arima_pred$mean

#' @calculate MSE, MAE, MAPE for the above combination forecast
#'

MSE_weighted = mean((test_data_lm$CL-weighted_pred)^2)%>%sqrt()
MAE_weighted = mean(abs(test_data_lm$CL-weighted_pred))
MAPE_weighted = mean(abs(1-weighted_pred/test_data_lm$CL))*100

res4 = cbind (MSE_weighted,MAE_weighted,MAPE_weighted)
res44 = rbind(res4,res33)
colnames(res44) = c("MSE","MAE","MAPE")
rownames(res44) = c("Combined_Weighted","Combined_equalWeight","ARIMA Model","TFN Model","LM")
kable(res44, digits = 2, caption = "Out-of-sample Forecasts Accuracy")
